1342
00:54:17,580 --> 00:54:20,240
So the way to think
about this whole system,

1343
00:54:20,240 --> 00:54:21,980
again, is you've got adenosine building up

1344
00:54:21,980 --> 00:54:24,090
depending on how long you've been awake

1345
00:54:24,090 --> 00:54:25,150
and it's making you sleepy,

1346
00:54:25,150 --> 00:54:26,820
and then you've got the
circadian mechanisms

1347
00:54:26,820 --> 00:54:28,490
that are timing your wakefulness

1348
00:54:28,490 --> 00:54:30,090
and timing when you wanna be asleep,

1349
00:54:30,090 --> 00:54:32,400
mainly through cortisol and melatonin,

1350
00:54:32,400 --> 00:54:33,470
but there are a bunch of other things

1351
00:54:33,470 --> 00:54:35,560
that are downstream of
cortisol and melatonin,

1352
00:54:35,560 --> 00:54:40,080
like, we tend to be hungrier
during our wakeful period

1353
00:54:40,080 --> 00:54:41,030
than late at night,

1354
00:54:41,030 --> 00:54:42,800
some people like to eat late at night,

1355
00:54:42,800 --> 00:54:44,390
but if you're finding that you

1356
00:54:44,390 --> 00:54:46,820
can't become a day person
or a morning person,

1357
00:54:46,820 --> 00:54:50,010
shifting your light exposure, exercise,

1358
00:54:50,010 --> 00:54:52,950
and food intake to the daytime will help.

1359
00:54:52,950 --> 00:54:56,750
Some people like to stop
eating around 6:00 or 8:00 p.m.

1360
00:54:56,750 --> 00:54:58,930
because of metabolic reasons

1361
00:54:58,930 --> 00:55:01,340
or they're trying to maintain
their weight or lose weight,

1362
00:55:01,340 --> 00:55:05,690
that's actually not supported
so well by the literature,

1363
00:55:05,690 --> 00:55:07,510
the literature around
nutrition essentially says

1364
00:55:07,510 --> 00:55:09,880
that it's best to restrict your feeding

1365
00:55:09,880 --> 00:55:12,120
to a certain period of each 24-hour cycle

1366
00:55:12,120 --> 00:55:14,180
to not be eating around the clock,

